-- Abengoa, BP, Fiat, RBS, Total, UBS May Be Active: European Equity Preview
-- Whitney Kisling
-- 2010-07-05T02:50:11Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-05/abengoa-areva-bmw-bp-fiat-rbs-total-ubs-european-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in  European  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are from the last close.  
 The  Stoxx Europe 600 Index  slipped less than 0.1 percent to
237.27. The  Stoxx 50 Index  slid 0.4 percent to 2,296.63. The
 Euro Stoxx 50 Index , a benchmark for nations using the euro,
advanced 0.2 percent to 2,522.36.  
 Abengoa SA  (ABG SM): The Spanish energy company will
receive a $1.45 billion U.S. government loan guarantee for a 250
megawatt solar power plant in Arizona, according to White House
documents. The shares rose 1.9 percent to 16.52 euros.  
 Alstom SA  (ALO FP): The French maker of TGV high-speed
trains is in a consortium bidding for a high-speed rail project
to link the Saudi coastal city of Jeddah with Mecca and Medina,
the Saudi Railways Organization said in a statement. The shares
rose 32 cents, or 0.9 percent, to 36.87 euros.  
 Areva SA  (CEI FP): The world’s biggest maker of nuclear
reactors is in talks to sell more of its EPR reactors to India
and China, Chief Executive Officer Anne Lauvergeon said. The
shares rose 50 cents, or 0.2 percent, to 333.90 euros.  
 AS Roma SpA  (ASR IM): The Sensi family may agree to hand
over the ownership of Compagnia Italpetroli SpA, which controls
the Italian soccer club, to UniCredit SpA, Il Sole 24 Ore said,
without saying where it got the information. AS Roma rose 0.6
percent to 90.6 euro cents.  
 Atlantia SpA  (ATL IM): Italy’s largest toll highway
operator, the Gavio group and  Mediobanca SpA  will list the toll-
road operators they control in Chile,  Corriere della Sera  said,
without saying where it got the information. Atlantia shares
gained 1 percent to 14.6 euros.  
 Barco NV  (BAR BB): The Belgian maker of digital cinema
projectors said it won a contract to supply 600 of the
projectors to Chinese movie-theater operator Dadi Digital Cinema
Ltd. Barco lost 1.6 percent to 38 euros.  
 Bank Sarasin & Cie AG  (BSAN SW): Chief Executive Officer
Joachim Straehle said he would be “astounded” to see Rabobank
Groep sell its stake in the Swiss private bank, according to an
interview with Finanz und Wirtschaft. The stock fell 1.2 percent
to 43 Swiss francs.  
 Bayerische Motoren Werke AG  (BMW GY): BMW and Mazda Motor
Corp. cars are under investigation by the U.S. auto-safety
regulator for possible defects that can cause the power steering
to fail, raising the risk of a crash. BMW shares fell 0.8
percent to 37.89 euros.  
 BP Plc  (BP/ LN): The oil company is seeking a strategic
investor that would help the company thwart takeover bids, the
Sunday Times reported, without saying where it got the
information. The shares fell 1.8 percent to 322 pence.  
 CNP Assurances  (CNP FP): The French insurer said it plans
to carry out a four-for-one stock split on July 5. The shares
rose 84 cents, or 1.5 percent, to 56 euros.  
 Dana Petroleum Plc  (DNX LN): Korea National Oil Corp.’s
offer for Dana Petroleum may value the company at 16.50 pounds
($25.06) a share, the London-based Times reported. The stock
advanced 22.3 percent to 1,440 pence.  
 Deutsche Bank AG (DBK GY): Deutsche Bank employees, who are
suspects in a nationwide probe over possible tax evasion linked
to trading of emissions allowances, were warned beforehand about
a raid in the case, a prosecutor said. The shares gained 0.1
percent to 45.06 euros.  
 EnBW Energie Baden-Wuerttemberg AG (EBK GY), E.ON AG (EOAN
GY) and  RWE AG  (RWE GY): Parliamentary leaders of Germany’s
government coalition agreed on extending the operating life of
the nation’s nuclear power plants by more than 10 years, Der
Spiegel reported, without saying where it got the information.
E.ON shares rose 0.5 percent to 22.14 euros. EnBW shares fell
2.5 percent to 37 euros. RWE shares gained 0.2 percent to 53.35
euros.  
 European Aeronautic Defence & Space Co.  (EAD FP): The World
Trade Organization’s decision that Airbus SAS benefited from
illegal subsidies won’t hinder development of the A350 long-
range airliner, EADS Chief Executive Officer Louis Gallois said.
Airbus will bid for a U.S. refueling tanker contract, he also
said. The shares fell 59 cents, or 3.6 percent, to 15.80 euros.  
 Fiat SpA  (F IM): The Italian carmaker may set the timetable
for the spinoff of its agricultural and truckmaking units from
its car division at a board meeting on July 21,  Corriere della
Sera  said, without saying where it got the information. The
shares increased 0.4 percent to 8.22 euros.  
 Intesa Sanpaolo SpA  (ISP IM) and  UniCredit SpA  (UCG IM):
European banks may be active after French Finance Minister
Christine Lagarde said that stress tests will show that Europe’s
banks are “solid and healthy.” Intesa and UniCredit, Italy’s
biggest banks, rose 0.4 percent to 2.15 euros and 1.82 euros,
respectively.  
 Landi Renzo SpA  (LR IM): The maker of injection systems for
alternative fuels is considering making an acquisition in the
U.S., Il Sole 24 Ore reported, without saying where it got the
information. The shares dropped 4.7 percent to 2.86 euros.  
 Nyrstar NV  (NYR BB): The world’s largest zinc producer said
it spent almost 3.95 million euros ($4.96 million) to buy back
435,000 shares on June 25 and June 28. Nyrstar advanced 0.4
percent to 8.12 euros.  
 Royal Bank of Scotland Group Plc  (RBS LN): The U.K.’s
biggest government-owned bank expects that the state will start
selling its stake in the lender in 2011, RBS Chief Executive
Officer Stephen Hester told Welt am Sonntag. The shares advanced
1.5 percent to 40.06 pence.  
 Siemens AG  (SIE GY): Europe’s biggest engineering company
may sell its Austrian financial unit Innovest to Raiffeisen
Capital Management in the coming days, Wirtschaftsblatt
newspaper reported, citing unidentified people familiar with the
negotiations. The shares fell 1.4 percent to 71.72 euros.  
 Sol Melia SA  (SOL SM): The Spanish resort operator with
properties in 26 countries will focus on acquisitions abroad,
Chief Executive Officer Gabriel Escarrer told El Pais. The stock
rose 1.8 percent to 5.14 euros.  
 Total SA (FP FP): The French oil company hasn’t considered
bidding for BP Plc, Chief Executive Officer Christophe de
Margerie said. The shares rose 31 cents, or 0.9 percent, to
36.19 euros.  
 UBS AG (UBSN VX): The Swiss bank will invest more than 100
million francs ($94.1 million) in its domestic operations over
the next three years, NZZ am Sonntag cited Lukas Gaehwiler, the
head of its Swiss business, as saying. The stock rose 0.3
percent to 14.06 francs.  
